title: For Sale:  Browning A5 12ga Made by Remington 1905-1910
postcontent:
This one was made between 1905-1910 according to the SN, 50xxx.  The lack of a letter at the start of the SN indicates it was not one of the later Browning's made by Remington, thus is significantly more rare.  I inherited this one and it appears to be all original.  The stock does have a few dings and there is a hairline crack in the foregrip which would not affect function. Everything seems to be working just fine.

Here's some background on these:
When John Browning sold his ( right to manufacture ) Autoloading Shotgun to Fabrique Nationale in March of 1902, he reserved the right to sell in the United States. FN could only sell outside of the US. In order to show his trust in the new gun, John Browning made an agreement to purchase 10,000 guns. These guns were to be marked "BROWNING AUTOMATIC ARMS Co", and he would distribute through the Browning Bros. Company in Ogden Utah. Not all 10,000 guns were actually delivered due to contract disputes later on with Remington (another story)In 1903, after John Browning returned from Belgium, he sold the manufacturing rights to Remington for sales in the US only. Remington started manufacturing in 1905, it was an instant success in the US. One of the agreements with Remington was to start the serial numbers of these guns at 10,000. He didn't want FN guns with the same serial numbers as the Remingtons. (Remington historians are still trying to figure out why they started at 10K)Production continued at Remington until 1910 when the change was made in the model number and the gun became the Remington Model 11.

Note:  From 1940-46 Remington produced the A5.  These have the letter A (16ga), B(12ga) or C (20ga) in front of the SN (which the one being offered does not).

$750 OBO.  Will consider trades.  Thanks for looking!

Has a beautiful high gloss mannlicher style stock with a Monte Carlo cheek piece. The rifle has never been fired. The stock has a few very small dings from moving but nothing major, the overall condition is excellent. The rifle is missing the bolt, which is why I'm trying to sell/trade it. I absolutely love this gun and hate to see it go, but I just don't have the time to invest in completing the action. Would make a fantastic project gun or would be great for a collector. These guns are very rare and hard to find, but have a prestige like none other for accuracy and feel.

Factory New





The P-3AT is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the .380 Auto cartridge. It has been developed from our highly successful P-32 pistol with negligible increase in weight and size. The slidestop has been eliminated and the magazine capacity reduced to 6 rounds due to the larger cartridge. The firing mechanism is double action only. The magazine has a 6 round capacity. The KEL-TEC P-3AT is the lightest .380 Auto pistol ever made. Thanks to its locking dynamics and superior ergonometry, perceived recoil and practical accuracy are comparable to much larger guns. The P-3AT is mainly intended for plainclothes police officers as a secondary weapon, or for concealed carry by licensed citizens. The small grip size and light trigger pull make the P-3AT ideal for female shooters.



The P-3AT has five main component groups: barrel, slide, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 ordnance steel, heat treated to 48 HRC. The slide is also 4140 steel, and contains the firing pin and the extractor. The rectangular frame is machined from solid 7075-T6 aluminum and houses the firing mechanism. The trigger connects via a transfer bar to the hammer. The hammer is driven by a novel free floating extension spring. The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. After firing, the hammer block holds the hammer away from the firing pin, providing a mechanical safety.

Shoots smooth as silk. There is very light bluing loss on the sharp edges of the muzzle and the cylinder.

 The hand crafted nature and attention to detail of craftsmanship of these early Pythons is truly outstanding.

 Valuing the Python at $1600 firm with original generation 2 stocks in very good condition (used but no chips or cracks). Stocks themselves go for between $250 to $400
